# Resting HRV Measured by Consumer Wearables (raw notes)

**Primary source**: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12693838/  
**Reading date**: 2026-04-07  
**Status**: raw (do not modify)

---

## Key Findings

- Resting HRV measured by consumer wearables shows **small-to-moderate associations** with:
  - Depressive symptoms.
  - Sleep difficulties.
  - Other health and well-being indicators.[web:133]
- Within-person analyses: **higher daily HRV is associated with better perceived recovery and lower mental exhaustion** in at least one included study.[web:133]

## Relevance for V.I.T.A.L

- Confirms that **Apple Watch-level HRV is good enough** to capture meaningful mental health and recovery signals.
- Supports V.I.T.A.L’s design:
  - Use resting HRV trends as a core indicator.
  - Focus on **within-person changes over time**, not cross-person comparisons.

## Unknown / To Confirm

- Typical day-to-day HRV variability range to distinguish “noise” from meaningful change.